        <h2 id="examples">Local search ecosystem in practice</h2>
        <p>Here are three concrete cases showing how ecosystem-level thinking changes outcomes.</p>

        <h3>1. Multi-location restaurant chain</h3>
        <p>A 12-location restaurant group found that 4 locations were underperforming in local search despite having good food and solid review scores. Audit revealed those locations had inconsistent NAP across directories — old addresses from a previous move still live on Foursquare and YellowPages. After a citation cleanup and GBP re-verification, those 4 locations saw a 60% increase in GBP impressions in the first quarter.</p>

        <h3>2. Emergency plumber — single location</h3>
        <p>A Denver plumber was invisible in Local Pack for "emergency plumber near me" despite 4 years in business. His GBP was unclaimed. Citations existed but had three different phone numbers across 22 directories. After claiming GBP, cleaning citations, and generating 15 new reviews in 60 days, he appeared consistently in the local 3-pack and averaged 3-5 inbound calls from Google weekly.</p>

        <h3>3. Hair salon — competitive market</h3>
        <p>A new salon owner spent her first 6 months doing excellent work but no local SEO. A competitor with equivalent reviews but a stronger citation footprint and active GBP posts dominated every "best hair salon near me" query in the city. The lesson: the ecosystem is competitive. Strong signals from a competitor actively limit your visibility even when your reviews are good.</p>

